00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:23.400
This novel, what it's about
essentially, is a group of nuns.

00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:26.080
Sorry, I wrote about nuns.

00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:30.780
In a small convent
in, yes, Brooklyn.

00:02:30.780 --> 00:02:32.460
A group of nursing sisters.

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:37.250
This is an order that's sort of
an amalgamation of many orders

00:02:37.250 --> 00:02:39.900
that actually existed,
but I had to create my own

00:02:39.900 --> 00:02:42.620
for the purposes of the fiction.

00:02:42.620 --> 00:02:48.350 position:56%
A group of women who essentially
served the poor in every kind of way

00:02:48.350 --> 00:02:54.160
from babysitting to housecleaning,
to actual nursing, childbirth,

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:57.410
all that in these neighborhoods.

00:02:57.410 --> 00:03:04.040
In the novel they sort
of adopt a young widow.

00:03:04.040 --> 00:03:06.500
Her husband has committed suicide.

00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:11.650
And the novel kind of follows
her life with the nuns,

00:03:11.650 --> 00:03:17.700
but it's also about the
generation looking back at this.

00:03:17.700 --> 00:03:21.720
That's kind of what
the story is about.

00:03:21.720 --> 00:03:25.610
But the meaning for
me, of the novel,

00:03:25.610 --> 00:03:32.280
or what I wrote the novel for,
I suppose, is more of a kind

00:03:32.280 --> 00:03:36.200
of a meditation on selflessness,

00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:42.590
a concept that I think is fading
rapidly in the 21st Century,

00:03:42.590 --> 00:03:47.990
that sense of giving of one's self.

00:03:47.990 --> 00:03:55.860
And oddly enough, one of the sparks
for this novel had nothing to do

00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:59.810
with Brooklyn or nuns,
or Catholicism.

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:03.700
I really thought maybe I was
going to escape all those things

00:04:03.700 --> 00:04:09.260
in this novel, because the very
first germ of the story which came

00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:13.930
to me years and years ago arose
out of a conversation I've had

00:04:13.930 --> 00:04:19.680
with a friend who had a vague
recollection of a man who lived

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:24.640
in his grandfather's
house way upstate New York

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:30.040
who had been his grandfather's
substitute in The Civil War,

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:32.030
or his great grandfather.

00:04:32.030 --> 00:04:36.730
And the idea of substitute
just fascinated me,

00:04:36.730 --> 00:04:42.880
and it sort of had resonance of
the military now, the substitutes,

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:45.520
the people who go so
we don't have to.

00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:48.090
And I started doing just
research like maybe I'm going

00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:49.970
to write a Civil War novel.

00:04:49.970 --> 00:04:52.740
Wouldn't that surprise everyone?

00:04:54.540 --> 00:04:59.350
[Laughter] Eventually that became
a very small part of the novel.

00:04:59.350 --> 00:05:05.860
But that idea of taking someone's
place, putting your own life

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:10.780
on the lin for someone else either
for money, as many substitutes

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:15.680
in The Civil War did,
for some greater good,

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:17.100
for some greater glory.

00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:19.950
And then as soon as I got to the
greater glory, I thought, oh, my,

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:22.510
God, it's going to be
another Catholic novel.

00:05:22.510 --> 00:05:25.110
[ Laughter ]

00:05:25.110 --> 00:05:27.020
&gt;&gt; Lynn Neary: Well, I have to
