I just noticed during the course

00:43:35.980 --> 00:43:39.440
of our conversation you're a
little self-conscious about writing

00:43:39.440 --> 00:43:41.090
about nuns, writing
about Catholicism.

00:43:41.090 --> 00:43:42.390
&gt;&gt; Alice McDermott: Did you notice?

00:43:42.390 --> 00:43:43.690
Right.

00:43:43.690 --> 00:43:44.990
&gt;&gt; Lynn Neary: Everything
about the Irish.

00:43:44.990 --> 00:43:46.290
Just, why?

00:43:46.290 --> 00:43:47.590 position:56%
Because it's kind of worked for you.

00:43:47.590 --> 00:43:52.410
[Laughter] And you
do a good job of it.

00:43:52.410 --> 00:43:55.930
&gt;&gt; Alice McDermott: You
know, I guess I resist.

00:43:55.930 --> 00:43:57.710
You know, there's a
difference between.

00:43:57.710 --> 00:44:01.330
And this is true of literary
fiction, not all fiction.

00:44:01.330 --> 00:44:06.980 position:56%
There's a difference between what a
book is about and what a book means.

00:44:06.980 --> 00:44:12.440
And I think maybe just because
of promotional aspects of it,

00:44:12.440 --> 00:44:16.800
we don't talk enough about what
books mean, what the story means,

00:44:16.800 --> 00:44:22.410
why this story is being told, what
this story invites us to consider.

00:44:22.410 --> 00:44:27.460
I think we talk too much about
what's happening in the story.

00:44:27.460 --> 00:44:30.890
So not that it needs to
be a moral, you know,

00:44:30.890 --> 00:44:35.720
but you know when you tell a kid
a story about the Big Bad Wolf,

00:44:35.720 --> 00:44:38.160
they take it literally, you know.

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:40.880 position:56%
It's like, well, where does he live?

00:44:40.880 --> 00:44:43.780
If I go there, is there
a wolf on our block?

00:44:43.780 --> 00:44:46.390
But as you get a little
older you understand, oh,

00:44:46.390 --> 00:44:51.120
you're telling me this because you
want me to think about what I say

00:44:51.120 --> 00:44:56.660 position:56%
and I shouldn't lie, and I shouldn't
make up over- emotional scenes.

00:44:56.660 --> 00:44:57.960
Oh, I understand.

00:44:57.960 --> 00:45:01.860
And I think somehow we've
gotten to be a reading public

00:45:01.860 --> 00:45:04.620
that talks an awful lot about
what happens in the book

00:45:04.620 --> 00:45:08.620
and who the characters are, and
who got killed when and why.

00:45:08.620 --> 00:45:11.210
And I think we don't
spend enough time.

00:45:11.210 --> 00:45:13.690
Book clubs do this,
which is why I love them.

00:45:13.690 --> 00:45:14.990
What do you think?

00:45:14.990 --> 00:45:16.970
Why do you think this
story's being told?

00:45:16.970 --> 00:45:19.890
Why do you think these
things happened?

00:45:19.890 --> 00:45:24.700
If every detail counts, which
I think it should in fiction

00:45:24.700 --> 00:45:27.170
because we're making
all this stuff up,

00:45:27.170 --> 00:45:32.520
every detail is a conscious
choice that a fiction writer makes

00:45:32.520 --> 00:45:35.200
to keep it, to put it on the page.

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:37.960
And I love a reader who
looks at those details

00:45:37.960 --> 00:45:40.880
and says I wonder why
this is in here.

00:45:40.880 --> 00:45:43.930
I wonder what it means.

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:45.230
&gt;&gt; Lynn Neary: Thank you
so much, Alice McDermott.

00:45:45.230 --> 00:45:47.030
&gt;&gt; Alice McDermott: Thank you.

